It's just wild-eyed idealism.  Genomic modification and neural modification in
infancy are a hell of a lot easier than reversing the modification in
adulthood.  We can't rely on the "we'll be able to reverse it by the time
they're 18" to solve the moral issues.  Plus, I don't think that argument is
correct.  Neuromod will be the real hot-spot issue, and neuromod is almost
